265
00:12:47,505 --> 00:12:50,815
(Returning to the stage with a fluttering heart)

266
00:12:50,915 --> 00:12:51,915
(Scraping)

267
00:12:51,916 --> 00:12:53,715
(Peeking)

268
00:12:54,485 --> 00:12:55,715
You're so handsome.

269
00:12:56,955 --> 00:12:58,015
Thank you.

270
00:12:58,155 --> 00:13:00,125
(He finally got the attention he was seeking.)

271
00:13:00,825 --> 00:13:02,325
- I had to tell you.
- My goodness.

272
00:13:02,595 --> 00:13:03,955
Thank you. Thank you so much.

273
00:13:05,565 --> 00:13:06,895
Gosh, I'd better make it delicious.

274
00:13:07,325 --> 00:13:09,065
(Smiling)

275
00:13:09,295 --> 00:13:10,295
Okay.

276
00:13:10,296 --> 00:13:11,865
(He's ready to make it delicious.)

277
00:13:11,965 --> 00:13:16,575
(Stir-frying it without mercy like his mercilessly beautiful face)

278
00:13:16,975 --> 00:13:18,844
(It smells good.)

279
00:13:18,845 --> 00:13:20,375
You should try it.

280
00:13:21,075 --> 00:13:22,145
Enjoy.

281
00:13:23,215 --> 00:13:26,545
(Making a cool exit after his work is done)

282
00:13:27,615 --> 00:13:30,484
(His desire to experience youth has been resolved.)

283
00:13:30,485 --> 00:13:34,125
(He has returned to his post.)

284
00:13:34,855 --> 00:13:38,055
(It's been 2 hours and 30 minutes since opening.)

285
00:13:38,795 --> 00:13:42,665
(Night has fallen on Lyon.)

286
00:13:44,065 --> 00:13:48,635
(It's time to finish their dinners...)

287
00:13:49,275 --> 00:13:52,775
(and head back home to prepare for tomorrow.)

288
00:13:53,345 --> 00:13:56,615
(But there are still customers at the Single Pan House.)

289
00:13:57,075 --> 00:14:00,285
(Customers are coming even at late hours.)

290
00:14:01,145 --> 00:14:04,755
(Entering)

291
00:14:05,285 --> 00:14:07,955
(A father and daughter are heading upstairs.)

292
00:14:08,485 --> 00:14:11,395
(New customers are settling down at an outdoor table.)

293
00:14:11,655 --> 00:14:13,625
Are we still taking customers?

294
00:14:14,025 --> 00:14:16,134
Yes. They can be our last.

295
00:14:16,135 --> 00:14:17,265
For two?

296
00:14:17,665 --> 00:14:20,605
(The floor manager is trying to wrap up the day.)

297
00:14:21,005 --> 00:14:22,674
(Glaring)

298
00:14:22,675 --> 00:14:24,204
- Can we stop taking customers?
- Why?

299
00:14:24,205 --> 00:14:25,244
Should we continue?

300
00:14:25,245 --> 00:14:26,875
We have to make at least 2,000 euros.

301
00:14:28,445 --> 00:14:29,475
All right.

302
00:14:30,145 --> 00:14:32,715
(We're open.)

303
00:14:33,485 --> 00:14:34,984
Our sales are important.

304
00:14:34,985 --> 00:14:36,154
(He intends to make good sales.)

305
00:14:36,155 --> 00:14:37,355
Don't you think so?

306
00:14:37,915 --> 00:14:38,954
(Dark)

307
00:14:38,955 --> 00:14:41,685
(Other shops are closing early as it's a weekday.)

308
00:14:42,455 --> 00:14:44,955
(But thanks to the bright sign...)

309
00:14:45,225 --> 00:14:46,225
Good morning.

310
00:14:46,226 --> 00:14:47,595
(He's saying a morning greeting.)

311
00:14:48,195 --> 00:14:49,564
Can you take these customers?

312
00:14:49,565 --> 00:14:50,695
(They keep getting more customers.)

313
00:14:51,035 --> 00:14:53,004
- Let's aim for 2,000 euros.
- Okay.

314
00:14:53,005 --> 00:14:54,465
(They'll reach their goal at this rate!)

315
00:14:55,405 --> 00:14:59,105
(The father and daughter are sitting on the 2nd floor.)

316
00:14:59,405 --> 00:15:01,405
I'll get a tartare...

317
00:15:02,575 --> 00:15:05,745
and the Korean meatball.

318
00:15:06,815 --> 00:15:08,415
- Are you ready to order?
- Yes.

319
00:15:09,315 --> 00:15:11,384
We'll get the main menu, but without the squid.

320
00:15:11,385 --> 00:15:12,524
Without the squid?

321
00:15:12,525 --> 00:15:14,455
- We have allergies.
- Okay.

322
00:15:14,925 --> 00:15:16,724
We'll also get an order of this.

323
00:15:16,725 --> 00:15:18,295
One tartare? Okay.

324
00:15:19,895 --> 00:15:20,895
(Additional 75 euros)

325
00:15:20,896 --> 00:15:22,094
(Order: 2 spicy stir-fried squid and pork without squid,)

326
00:15:22,095 --> 00:15:23,235
(1 beef tartare, 1 tteokgalbi, 1 Korean meatball, cocktail, water)

327
00:15:23,395 --> 00:15:26,235
- Excuse me. For Table Six, - Yes?

328
00:15:26,505 --> 00:15:30,775
can you make the main dish without any seafood?

329
00:15:31,205 --> 00:15:32,505
They have allergies.

330
00:15:32,745 --> 00:15:34,144
- Without seafood?
- Exactly.

331
00:15:34,145 --> 00:15:35,145
- The main dish?
- Yes.

332
00:15:35,146 --> 00:15:36,875
- Okay. Sure.
- Thank you.

333
00:15:37,815 --> 00:15:40,585
(Jang Woo is quick to prepare the beef tartare.)

334
00:15:41,245 --> 00:15:43,984
(Ground garlic...)

335
00:15:43,985 --> 00:15:47,385
(and soy sauce)

336
00:15:48,025 --> 00:15:50,455
(Covering it in sesame oil)

337
00:15:50,925 --> 00:15:54,495
(The secret is in his hands.)

338
00:15:55,395 --> 00:15:58,905
(With some green onions as garnish, it's ready.)

339
00:16:00,835 --> 00:16:01,905
Good evening.

340
00:16:02,605 --> 00:16:06,675
(All of their appetizers are served.)

341
00:16:10,545 --> 00:16:13,015
(Trying the beef tartare right away)

342
00:16:14,245 --> 00:16:15,485
It has sesame seeds.

343
00:16:17,215 --> 00:16:18,385
This is very good.

344
00:16:18,655 --> 00:16:21,755
(He fell in love with it after a single bite.)

345
00:16:22,995 --> 00:16:26,065
(A huge bite)

346
00:16:26,395 --> 00:16:28,895
I don't know why, but it tastes so familiar.

347
00:16:31,235 --> 00:16:36,035
(Did I taste it in my past life?)

348
00:16:36,475 --> 00:16:38,745
They added sesame seeds. What a great idea.

349
00:16:40,405 --> 00:16:43,445
(It tastes great.)

350
00:16:45,485 --> 00:16:49,215
(His hand subconsciously reaches for the salad.)

351
00:16:50,385 --> 00:16:54,185
(Naturally wrapping it around the tartare)

352
00:16:54,385 --> 00:16:57,925
(Indeed, this is what ssam is.)

353
00:17:00,965 --> 00:17:02,135
This is fantastic.

354
00:17:03,635 --> 00:17:05,504
(How delicious)

355
00:17:05,505 --> 00:17:09,135
I was a bit scared, but it's great. It's really delicious.

356
00:17:10,335 --> 00:17:11,475
Aren't you going to have some?

357
00:17:12,005 --> 00:17:13,475
I don't like tartare.

358
00:17:14,145 --> 00:17:16,475
(Then it's all for me.)

359
00:17:18,115 --> 00:17:20,815
You finished it all. You finished it clean.

360
00:17:21,285 --> 00:17:23,584
You ate it all. Was it that good?

361
00:17:23,585 --> 00:17:25,055
It's extremely good.

362
00:17:26,155 --> 00:17:27,485
It's not even sweet.

363
00:17:28,525 --> 00:17:31,395
(He cannot stop complimenting the beef tartare.)

364
00:17:32,695 --> 00:17:36,235
It's really delicious. What a fantastic idea.

365
00:17:36,835 --> 00:17:38,234
What was its name again?

366
00:17:38,235 --> 00:17:40,265
It was called "yukhoe."

367
00:17:40,505 --> 00:17:41,665
I need to remember it.

368
00:17:42,305 --> 00:17:43,804
(That moment)

369
00:17:43,805 --> 00:17:46,704
I'm impressed they made this with beef.

370
00:17:46,705 --> 00:17:49,175
What an idea. The name? I must remember it.

371
00:17:49,515 --> 00:17:53,144
(The other tables can hear him.)

372
00:17:53,145 --> 00:17:54,844
We should try that too.

373
00:17:54,845 --> 00:17:56,915
(We should try that too.)

374
00:17:58,185 --> 00:17:59,885
- The beef tartare?
- Yes.

375
00:18:01,225 --> 00:18:04,225
(The news about the beef tartare is traveling.)

376
00:18:04,795 --> 00:18:07,325
(Right that moment, Roxana approaches them.)

377
00:18:07,595 --> 00:18:09,365
Could we try some sides?

378
00:18:09,935 --> 00:18:12,634
Sure. Do you need the menu?

379
00:18:12,635 --> 00:18:13,765
We already took a look.

380
00:18:14,805 --> 00:18:16,134
(What was it?)

381
00:18:16,135 --> 00:18:17,275
- Korean tartare.
- Okay.

382
00:18:18,675 --> 00:18:21,745
- And tteokgalbi.
- Tteokgalbi.

383
00:18:21,975 --> 00:18:24,345
(They're ordering some sides after hearing the news.)

384
00:18:24,745 --> 00:18:26,085
Do you see the woman behind you?

385
00:18:26,745 --> 00:18:27,745
Yes?

386
00:18:27,746 --> 00:18:30,184
They ordered a beef tartare...

387
00:18:30,185 --> 00:18:32,085
after you praised it.

388
00:18:32,755 --> 00:18:35,925
She kept looking this way when you were talking about it.

389
00:18:36,155 --> 00:18:39,725
(The daughter was watching the other table.)

390
00:18:40,795 --> 00:18:43,835
(The famous beef tartare is here.)

391
00:18:44,895 --> 00:18:47,335
(Amazing!)

392
00:18:48,235 --> 00:18:51,675
(Trying the famous tartare first)

393
00:18:55,815 --> 00:18:57,675
It's really good.

394
00:18:59,185 --> 00:19:02,815
(They almost missed out on it.)

395
00:19:03,085 --> 00:19:04,485
How is that?

396
00:19:04,585 --> 00:19:06,785
- It's good.
- It's very good.

397
00:19:07,725 --> 00:19:09,695
It's similar to our tartare.

398
00:19:11,795 --> 00:19:13,325
It's really good. I recommend it.

399
00:19:13,665 --> 00:19:16,935
There is garlic in it, so it doesn't feel so raw.

400
00:19:17,495 --> 00:19:20,405
(Thanks to the rumors, beef tartare orders are pouring in.)

401
00:19:23,475 --> 00:19:28,705
(There is a beef tartare craze at Single Pan House!)

402
00:19:32,445 --> 00:19:33,515
It's good.

403
00:19:34,945 --> 00:19:37,385
(It's time for dessert after their dinner.)

404
00:19:37,655 --> 00:19:39,085
Ice cream and crungji.

405
00:19:39,225 --> 00:19:41,185
Crungji made out of croissant is very good.

406
00:19:42,425 --> 00:19:44,955
(Wait...)

407
00:19:49,795 --> 00:19:51,334
But the croissant is French.

408
00:19:51,335 --> 00:19:53,665
No, it's not what you think.

409
00:19:54,405 --> 00:19:56,175
It's a flattened one.

410
00:19:56,275 --> 00:19:58,175
(Frowning)

411
00:19:58,705 --> 00:20:01,305
A flattened croissant? A croissant shouldn't be flattened.

412
00:20:01,805 --> 00:20:04,044
It's like how you don't mix tteokbokki and bibimbap.

413
00:20:04,045 --> 00:20:06,045
We don't flatten croissants.

414
00:20:06,115 --> 00:20:10,155
(This French customer is reacting passionately.)

415
00:20:10,355 --> 00:20:12,955
(But he is not the first one to be shocked by crungji.)

416
00:20:13,155 --> 00:20:15,755
(This table on the 2nd floor ordered a crungji earlier.)

417
00:20:16,225 --> 00:20:18,825
What is your opinion on this flattened croissant?

418
00:20:19,495 --> 00:20:21,164
It's heartbreaking to see as a French.

419
00:20:21,165 --> 00:20:22,225
A bit...

420
00:20:22,735 --> 00:20:24,564
They totally crushed the croissant.

421
00:20:24,565 --> 00:20:25,705
My gosh...

422
00:20:26,565 --> 00:20:29,334
What if you mix kimchi and vanilla?

423
00:20:29,335 --> 00:20:31,535
That's completely different.

424
00:20:32,875 --> 00:20:35,204
Is it illegal to add vanilla to kimchi?

425
00:20:35,205 --> 00:20:36,875
And a crushed croissant is okay?

426
00:20:38,045 --> 00:20:39,884
This is just a dessert.

427
00:20:39,885 --> 00:20:41,515
No, it's not just a dessert.

428
00:20:41,845 --> 00:20:43,055
It's a croissant.

429
00:20:43,555 --> 00:20:46,325
They crushed the French tradition.

430
00:20:47,425 --> 00:20:50,355
(Crungji became a topic of heated debates among the French.)

431
00:20:50,455 --> 00:20:53,865
We'll get two of these.

432
00:20:53,895 --> 00:20:57,365
(Will they change their minds after trying it?)

433
00:20:58,165 --> 00:21:01,965
(Opening the oven with anxiousness)

434
00:21:06,605 --> 00:21:09,145
(Freshly baked crungji)

435
00:21:10,475 --> 00:21:14,415
(Jang Woo is approaching after smelling the crungji.)

436
00:21:15,315 --> 00:21:18,915
(He cannot take his eyes off.)

437
00:21:19,525 --> 00:21:23,724
(Si Yoon is putting some ice cream on a ruined crungji.)

438
00:21:23,725 --> 00:21:24,825
Have it.

439
00:21:25,495 --> 00:21:27,265
(Thank you)

440
00:21:28,795 --> 00:21:29,865
(Moaning)

441
00:21:30,165 --> 00:21:31,435
(Tapping)

442
00:21:31,635 --> 00:21:34,035
(It's perfect for Jang Woo.)

443
00:21:34,935 --> 00:21:39,345
(Here comes freshly baked crungji!)

444
00:21:40,445 --> 00:21:41,775
Excuse me.

445
00:21:44,245 --> 00:21:45,615
- Thank you.
- Thank you.

446
00:21:46,715 --> 00:21:48,584
(He is leaving.)

447
00:21:48,585 --> 00:21:52,385
(Instead of leaving, he's standing by.)

448
00:21:53,625 --> 00:21:54,985
(Loitering)

449
00:21:55,355 --> 00:21:57,754
You can cut and eat it.

450
00:21:57,755 --> 00:21:58,825
- Enjoy.
- Thank you.

451
00:22:00,125 --> 00:22:02,665
(This side looks better in pictures.)

452
00:22:04,135 --> 00:22:08,035
(Making a slow exit after helping with the angle)

453
00:22:09,175 --> 00:22:11,135
How do you eat this? I don't understand.

454
00:22:12,605 --> 00:22:16,345
(The croissant looks too unfamiliar.)

455
00:22:16,875 --> 00:22:20,185
No, I... First...

456
00:22:20,245 --> 00:22:23,014
(Trying his best to cut it)

457
00:22:23,015 --> 00:22:24,055
Gosh.

458
00:22:25,015 --> 00:22:29,225
(It's hard to cut.)

459
00:22:29,625 --> 00:22:31,095
I'm going to break it all.

460
00:22:33,065 --> 00:22:34,125
Do you want me to do it?

461
00:22:35,565 --> 00:22:37,035
Yes, you try.

462
00:22:38,065 --> 00:22:40,635
(While his friend helps...)

463
00:22:43,005 --> 00:22:44,605
Let's just eat it. I'm impatient.

464
00:22:45,775 --> 00:22:49,275
(This customer was against crungji. What will be his reaction?)

465
00:22:51,215 --> 00:22:52,684
(Eating)

466
00:22:52,685 --> 00:22:55,045
(Amazed)

467
00:22:55,585 --> 00:22:57,455
(My goodness)

468
00:22:57,485 --> 00:22:58,815
(It's good!)

469
00:22:59,655 --> 00:23:02,055
(The other friend is trying it too.)

470
00:23:02,185 --> 00:23:04,255
(Amazing!)

471
00:23:04,495 --> 00:23:05,925
It's nice and sweet.

472
00:23:06,665 --> 00:23:10,235
(Adding some ice cream to the bite)

473
00:23:10,335 --> 00:23:11,535
(Delicious!)

474
00:23:12,805 --> 00:23:14,305
It's good with the ice cream.

475
00:23:15,265 --> 00:23:17,075
Yes, it's much better with the ice cream.

476
00:23:17,335 --> 00:23:18,335
Yes.

477
00:23:18,575 --> 00:23:20,774
(Crungji...)

478
00:23:20,775 --> 00:23:22,474
(and ice cream)

479
00:23:22,475 --> 00:23:25,915
(The perfect combination)

480
00:23:27,045 --> 00:23:29,755
- Is it good?
- Well, not bad.

481
00:23:30,755 --> 00:23:32,525
Not good, not bad.

482
00:23:32,655 --> 00:23:34,485
(Having another bite)

483
00:23:36,595 --> 00:23:38,524
(He said it was so-so, but...)

484
00:23:38,525 --> 00:23:40,795
(Another bite)

485
00:23:42,695 --> 00:23:44,835
(Covering it in melted ice cream)

486
00:23:46,005 --> 00:23:48,135
(Eating)

487
00:23:48,335 --> 00:23:49,475
(Delicious)

488
00:23:52,275 --> 00:23:54,705
So, do you like flattened croissants?

489
00:23:54,905 --> 00:23:57,515
Yes. I think I've started to like flattened croissants.

490
00:24:00,885 --> 00:24:04,455
(Finishing off the last piece)

491
00:24:05,255 --> 00:24:09,225
(It's been 3 hours and 30 minutes since opening.)

492
00:24:09,925 --> 00:24:13,695
(Things slow down at the gourmet alley at this hour.)

493
00:24:14,665 --> 00:24:18,735
(Some shops are closing.)

494
00:24:24,305 --> 00:24:27,745
(Two people are heading for the Single Pan House.)

495
00:24:28,405 --> 00:24:31,675
(They are shown to a table outside.)

496
00:24:33,045 --> 00:24:36,154
We will take anything that you can still make. Really.

497
00:24:36,155 --> 00:24:37,655
- Anything?
- Anything.

498
00:24:37,685 --> 00:24:38,785
Are you hungry?

499
00:24:39,115 --> 00:24:41,884
- Yes. A little bit.
- A little hungry?

500
00:24:41,885 --> 00:24:44,554
- So we have five small plates.
- Yes.

501
00:24:44,555 --> 00:24:45,865
(Studying the menu together for their order)

502
00:24:46,125 --> 00:24:48,594
Let me set this right here. I'll get you some more napkins.

503
00:24:48,595 --> 00:24:50,835
- Thank you so much.
- Of course.

504
00:24:51,065 --> 00:24:52,565
We have a new order!

505
00:24:54,765 --> 00:24:56,274
We're so lucky...

506
00:24:56,275 --> 00:24:58,934
we closed the kitchen earlier.

507
00:24:58,935 --> 00:25:01,174
We closed 15 minutes earlier.

508
00:25:01,175 --> 00:25:02,175
Thank you.

509
00:25:02,176 --> 00:25:03,874
Where do you work? Around here?

510
00:25:03,875 --> 00:25:06,714
We work maybe a ten-minute walk away.

511
00:25:06,715 --> 00:25:09,184
- Is it ten minutes away?
- We work at a Thai restaurant.

512
00:25:09,185 --> 00:25:11,214
- Thai restaurant.
- It's next to...

513
00:25:11,215 --> 00:25:12,784
- Next to the theater?
- Yes.

514
00:25:12,785 --> 00:25:14,184
- Next to the theater.
- Okay, I see.

515
00:25:14,185 --> 00:25:16,395
Yes, close to the theater and Hotel de Ville.

516
00:25:16,455 --> 00:25:17,524
I see.

517
00:25:17,525 --> 00:25:20,495
I haven't been able to walk around a lot.

518
00:25:21,125 --> 00:25:22,165
We've been working.

519
00:25:22,525 --> 00:25:24,764
- Just like...
- Work, work, work.

520
00:25:24,765 --> 00:25:27,165
Were there a lot of customers when you opened?

521
00:25:27,235 --> 00:25:29,504
Yes. And during the weekend, there were a lot of people.

522
00:25:29,505 --> 00:25:31,004
- Yes, sure.
- Yes.

523
00:25:31,005 --> 00:25:33,144
You should go to Fourviere.

524
00:25:33,145 --> 00:25:35,004
- It's a big church.
- Where is that? Okay.

525
00:25:35,005 --> 00:25:36,315
Let's say...

526
00:25:37,775 --> 00:25:42,985
(We'll show it to you in her place!)

527
00:25:44,515 --> 00:25:47,885
(The city of Lyon which we are in right now...)

528
00:25:49,725 --> 00:25:53,995
(is a city where the rivers Rhone and Saone meet.)

529
00:25:54,995 --> 00:25:58,495
(Rhone and Saone act as a rest area for the locals.)

530
00:25:58,865 --> 00:26:01,905
(It's also possible to swim here.)

531
00:26:02,535 --> 00:26:05,905
(You can meet famous Lyon representatives...)

532
00:26:06,505 --> 00:26:09,675
(on the Fresque des Lyonnais.)

533
00:26:09,915 --> 00:26:12,375
(Saint-Exupery wrote "The Little Prince.")

534
00:26:12,685 --> 00:26:15,045
(The Lumiere Brothers invented cinema.)

535
00:26:16,355 --> 00:26:19,285
(And this person is right at the center.)

536
00:26:19,755 --> 00:26:22,795
(Legendary French Chef, Paul Bocuse)

537
00:26:23,395 --> 00:26:25,125
(Beside his mural...)

538
00:26:25,725 --> 00:26:30,865
(is the Paul Bocuse Market named after him.)

539
00:26:31,265 --> 00:26:34,535
(This maze-like market...)

540
00:26:35,335 --> 00:26:39,305
(is a food pantry that has everything you might need.)

541
00:26:39,805 --> 00:26:43,075
(Most chefs in Lyon buy their ingredients here.)

542
00:26:43,415 --> 00:26:45,945
(And the representative dish)

543
00:26:46,985 --> 00:26:50,055
(French home cuisine, Buchon)

544
00:26:50,615 --> 00:26:53,055
(In addition, there is the Notre-Dame,)

545
00:26:53,655 --> 00:26:56,055
(Place Bellecour,)

546
00:26:56,655 --> 00:26:59,255
(Ancient Theater of Fourviere,)

547
00:26:59,865 --> 00:27:02,995
(Fourviere, which John is curious about,)

548
00:27:04,135 --> 00:27:06,235
(and...)

549
00:27:07,435 --> 00:27:09,975
(Single Pan House, which is at the center of it all.)

550
00:27:10,335 --> 00:27:11,934
Have a good evening. Thank you very much.

551
00:27:11,935 --> 00:27:13,274
Goodnight.

552
00:27:13,275 --> 00:27:15,875
(The customers are leaving one by one.)

553
00:27:18,015 --> 00:27:19,115
Bye.

554
00:27:19,445 --> 00:27:21,545
- Thank you.
- Bye.

555
00:27:22,855 --> 00:27:25,885
(They worked for 4 hours and 30 minutes.)

556
00:27:26,055 --> 00:27:27,184
- Yes.
- Good work, everyone.

557
00:27:27,185 --> 00:27:28,454
- Good work!
- Good work!

558
00:27:28,455 --> 00:27:30,455
(Will they be able to reach their goal?)

559
00:27:31,155 --> 00:27:34,165
(The 7th night in Lyon is drawing in.)

560
00:27:35,795 --> 00:27:39,335
(A new sun has risen.)

561
00:27:39,805 --> 00:27:43,775
(It's time to reveal their sales.)

562
00:27:44,375 --> 00:27:47,275
(They worked hard yesterday to reach their goal earlier.)

563
00:27:48,405 --> 00:27:51,745
(Did they make it?)

564
00:27:52,845 --> 00:27:54,045
- Should I press it?
- Yes.

565
00:27:55,015 --> 00:27:56,054
Ding.

566
00:27:56,055 --> 00:27:58,355
(Shall we take a look?)

567
00:27:58,585 --> 00:28:00,654
I think the font got bigger.

568
00:28:00,655 --> 00:28:01,685
You're right.

569
00:28:02,355 --> 00:28:03,554
Today, I feel like it says, "Welcome,"

570
00:28:03,555 --> 00:28:05,924
- "Chef Paik!" - "Chef Paik!"

571
00:28:05,925 --> 00:28:07,065
Something like that.

572
00:28:07,495 --> 00:28:09,995
I'm getting a good feeling just from the font.

573
00:28:10,135 --> 00:28:12,335
It's our last day today.

574
00:28:13,335 --> 00:28:15,434
- That must be why I'm happy.
- Yes.

575
00:28:15,435 --> 00:28:17,075
- I like it.
- Is that why?

576
00:28:17,705 --> 00:28:18,975
How much do we need?

577
00:28:20,675 --> 00:28:22,304
- About 3,000 dollars.
- Around 3,000 dollars.

578
00:28:22,305 --> 00:28:23,344
(They need to make 3,300 dollars to reach their goal.)

579
00:28:23,345 --> 00:28:25,614
- It's 2,000.
- If we made over 2,000 euros,

580
00:28:25,615 --> 00:28:27,084
- We'll go over for sure.
- we will make it.

581
00:28:27,085 --> 00:28:28,585
(If they make over 3,300 dollars, they'll make 1 million a year!)

582
00:28:28,745 --> 00:28:31,655
(In previous stages, Chef Paik...)

583
00:28:31,885 --> 00:28:35,425
(Stage 1: Earn 3,000 dirhams in Morocco)

584
00:28:35,485 --> 00:28:37,525
(Mission failed, game over)

585
00:28:37,695 --> 00:28:40,895
(Stage 2: Make 500,000 dollars a year in Italy)

586
00:28:40,925 --> 00:28:42,965
(Mission failed, game over)

587
00:28:43,035 --> 00:28:46,604
(Stage 3: Become a top restaurant in San Sebastian)

588
00:28:46,605 --> 00:28:48,564
(Mission failed, game over)

589
00:28:48,565 --> 00:28:51,735
(Chef Paik failed every time.)

590
00:28:52,735 --> 00:28:56,375
(How about this time in France?)

591
00:28:56,945 --> 00:28:59,585
I have a feeling we went over 1,700 euros at least.

592
00:28:59,945 --> 00:29:01,585
- No way...
- Just go.

593
00:29:02,645 --> 00:29:05,085
(Drumroll)

594
00:29:05,355 --> 00:29:07,025
- It's 1,700 euros?
- It's 1,500 euros.

595
00:29:07,425 --> 00:29:09,385
- It's 1,600 euros?
- It's 1,500 euros.

596
00:29:12,355 --> 00:29:16,065
(Will they prematurely reach their goal of 1 million in 7 days?)

597
00:29:16,235 --> 00:29:21,035
(Or will they go to work enthusiastically for their goal?)

598
00:29:21,205 --> 00:29:23,805
(Revealing yesterday's sales)

599
00:29:23,875 --> 00:29:26,874
(Single Pan House, day 7 sales)

600
00:29:26,875 --> 00:29:29,945
(1,986 euros)

601
00:29:30,175 --> 00:29:31,974
- What?
- That's a lot!

602
00:29:31,975 --> 00:29:33,345
(Hey! We earned a lot!)

603
00:29:34,885 --> 00:29:35,984
We made a lot.

604
00:29:35,985 --> 00:29:38,155
(It looks like they are likely to reach their goal.)

605
00:29:38,485 --> 00:29:39,524
Did we make a record?

606
00:29:39,525 --> 00:29:40,525
(The final result is...)

607
00:29:41,425 --> 00:29:43,255
Did we reach it?

608
00:29:43,795 --> 00:29:45,954
Wait, are we 100 dollars short?

609
00:29:45,955 --> 00:29:49,295
(They are finished if they can fill up the bar.)

610
00:29:57,875 --> 00:30:00,804
(There is a small gap!)

611
00:30:00,805 --> 00:30:03,545
(They failed to reach it early.)

612
00:30:04,575 --> 00:30:06,045
What is that?

613
00:30:07,045 --> 00:30:10,015
(No...)

614
00:30:10,085 --> 00:30:11,555
How much are we short?

615
00:30:12,055 --> 00:30:13,354
(Chef Paik's goal this time)

616
00:30:13,355 --> 00:30:15,824
(To open a restaurant with sales of 1 million dollars a year)

617
00:30:15,825 --> 00:30:16,954
(Sales of 1 million dollars a year...)

618
00:30:16,955 --> 00:30:19,255
(converted to 8 days equals...)

619
00:30:19,425 --> 00:30:20,624
(13,521 euros.)

620
00:30:20,625 --> 00:30:25,135
(Currency at the time was 1,625 won per euro.)

621
00:30:25,365 --> 00:30:28,134
(Progress to making 1 million dollars a year)

622
00:30:28,135 --> 00:30:34,004
(Including yesterday's sales...)

623
00:30:34,005 --> 00:30:39,845
(They made a total of 13,421 euros in 7 days.)

624
00:30:39,985 --> 00:30:42,955
(They are exactly 100 euros short.)

625
00:30:43,085 --> 00:30:44,354
No way.

626
00:30:44,355 --> 00:30:45,615
(They failed to finish early because of 100 euros.)

627
00:30:46,685 --> 00:30:48,585
We only had to take one more table.

628
00:30:49,725 --> 00:30:50,794
What?

629
00:30:50,795 --> 00:30:51,795
(What? Is this my fault?)

630
00:30:51,796 --> 00:30:53,495
We are exactly 100 euros short.

631
00:30:53,825 --> 00:30:54,894
You should have sold three crungjis...

632
00:30:54,895 --> 00:30:57,495
while I was doing the dishes!

633
00:30:58,365 --> 00:30:59,834
That is only ten euros.

634
00:30:59,835 --> 00:31:01,635
Are we three dollars short?

635
00:31:01,805 --> 00:31:04,374
Why are you all blaming me?

636
00:31:04,375 --> 00:31:06,574
- Let me clarify.
- This is a joke, right?

637
00:31:06,575 --> 00:31:08,245
We're 100 euros short.

638
00:31:09,145 --> 00:31:11,144
- It means...
- How strange.

639
00:31:11,145 --> 00:31:14,284
I swear I told you we should charge more.

640
00:31:14,285 --> 00:31:17,655
I told you our dishes were too cheap.

641
00:31:17,715 --> 00:31:20,685
I suggested we should raise all the prices.

642
00:31:21,325 --> 00:31:22,884
- We're...
- Don't blame it on me.

643
00:31:22,885 --> 00:31:24,024
You're right.

644
00:31:24,025 --> 00:31:27,565
I'm really taken aback.

645
00:31:27,865 --> 00:31:31,234
(They must go to work to make 100 more euros.)

646
00:31:31,235 --> 00:31:32,865
We were so close.

647
00:31:33,065 --> 00:31:34,805
We could have had a day off.

648
00:31:35,405 --> 00:31:36,574
It's too bad.

649
00:31:36,575 --> 00:31:37,575
(They feel a great sense of regret.)

650
00:31:37,576 --> 00:31:40,345
That gap is really annoying me.

651
00:31:41,375 --> 00:31:42,505
- It's annoying, isn't it?
- Yes.

652
00:31:43,675 --> 00:31:46,545
(Hurry up and go to work!)

653
00:31:46,885 --> 00:31:48,884
(Chef Paik fails to finish early.)

654
00:31:48,885 --> 00:31:50,055
Let's go.

655
00:31:50,655 --> 00:31:52,354
(So, you're back.)

656
00:31:52,355 --> 00:31:54,624
Okay, let's go.

657
00:31:54,625 --> 00:31:56,055
(Let's go for our last day.)

658
00:31:58,555 --> 00:32:01,295
Last day.

659
00:32:04,035 --> 00:32:05,194
Last day.

660
00:32:05,195 --> 00:32:06,604
(The last day's driver is John.)

661
00:32:06,605 --> 00:32:07,805
Let's go!

662
00:32:08,435 --> 00:32:10,835
(The chef and the sous chef of Single Pan House are ready.)

663
00:32:11,005 --> 00:32:12,535
We'll be back after our last day.

664
00:32:13,305 --> 00:32:15,104
Last day. Let's do this.

665
00:32:15,105 --> 00:32:16,675
(Everyone is ready to go.)

666
00:32:16,745 --> 00:32:17,845
It's our last day.

667
00:32:18,545 --> 00:32:20,185
- It's the last day.
- Last day.

668
00:32:20,685 --> 00:32:21,715
How exciting!

669
00:32:22,345 --> 00:32:23,755
Let's go for our last day.

670
00:32:24,055 --> 00:32:25,184
Let's step on it.

671
00:32:25,185 --> 00:32:26,855
(Leaving on high energy)

672
00:32:28,655 --> 00:32:30,225
Let's go for our last day.

673
00:32:30,595 --> 00:32:33,225
(Good luck with your last day!)

674
00:32:33,565 --> 00:32:36,834
I feel like it was just yesterday when we shot on this bridge.

675
00:32:36,835 --> 00:32:39,264
- The insert?
- The intro. It's already over.

676
00:32:39,265 --> 00:32:40,704
(The time passed fast.)

677
00:32:40,705 --> 00:32:42,665
I thought it would never end,

678
00:32:42,835 --> 00:32:44,975
but it went by fast. It ended in a flash.

679
00:32:45,405 --> 00:32:46,745
It really did.

680
00:32:47,245 --> 00:32:50,815
(Let's do our best until we reach our goal.)

681
00:32:52,315 --> 00:32:53,614
Let's wrap up well today.

682
00:32:53,615 --> 00:32:55,014
- Let's go!
- Let's go!

683
00:32:55,015 --> 00:32:57,915
(Let's wrap up well today.)

684
00:32:58,255 --> 00:32:59,314
(9:30am)

685
00:32:59,315 --> 00:33:01,885
(3 hours before opening)

686
00:33:03,425 --> 00:33:04,655
I grew fond of this place.

687
00:33:07,365 --> 00:33:09,125
The last day.

688
00:33:11,335 --> 00:33:12,564
(Clapping)

689
00:33:12,565 --> 00:33:14,464
(The floor manager is happy since it's the last day.)

690
00:33:14,465 --> 00:33:15,465
What are you doing?

691
00:33:15,935 --> 00:33:17,335
How exciting.

692
00:33:17,735 --> 00:33:20,475
(He's expressing his happiness with his whole body.)

693
00:33:21,045 --> 00:33:22,605
Let's do this. It's our last day.

694
00:33:23,215 --> 00:33:24,275
Let's change.

695
00:33:24,815 --> 00:33:25,974
Let's get dressed.

696
00:33:25,975 --> 00:33:28,685
(It's their last day. What menu will they serve?)

697
00:33:29,085 --> 00:33:30,185
(Heave-ho)

698
00:33:31,255 --> 00:33:33,555
(He's bringing out big slabs of meat with a grunt.)

699
00:33:33,755 --> 00:33:37,025
(What does he plan to do with them?)

700
00:33:37,625 --> 00:33:41,595
(There was a menu Chef Paik kept on mentioning.)

701
00:33:41,965 --> 00:33:44,665
(During a discussion before they opened)

702
00:33:44,865 --> 00:33:47,405
(Braised beef ribs could go in the center.)

703
00:33:47,505 --> 00:33:49,205
(That sounds delicious!)

704
00:33:49,665 --> 00:33:52,705
(It's for braised beef.)

705
00:33:53,275 --> 00:33:55,575
(Single Pan House showed off all kinds of meat dishes until now.)

706
00:33:55,975 --> 00:33:57,014
(The meat that will make the finale is...)

707
00:33:57,015 --> 00:33:59,615
(Beef)

708
00:34:00,385 --> 00:34:03,155
(A main dish we all think of when we talk about Korean food)

709
00:34:03,415 --> 00:34:07,755
(Braised beef ribs)

710
00:34:08,285 --> 00:34:11,695
(How will Chef Paik's braised beef ribs look?)

711
00:34:12,455 --> 00:34:15,795
(For braised beef ribs, they will use beef sirloin.)

712
00:34:16,495 --> 00:34:19,265
(After the blood is removed,)

713
00:34:20,065 --> 00:34:23,435
(the fatty part is cut off.)

714
00:34:27,345 --> 00:34:32,115
(Working on the hidden fat)

715
00:34:33,215 --> 00:34:39,055
(Once the meat is ready, cut it into smaller pieces.)

716
00:34:39,855 --> 00:34:44,955
(Now you have a lot of pieces for braised beef ribs.)

717
00:34:45,625 --> 00:34:47,365
- Si Yoon.
- What?

718
00:34:47,665 --> 00:34:48,825
Did you just talk casually?

719
00:34:49,395 --> 00:34:50,895
Is he doing that on purpose?

720
00:34:51,865 --> 00:34:54,265
I'm sorry... You guys sound similar.

721
00:34:55,535 --> 00:34:56,575
Si Yoon!

722
00:34:57,275 --> 00:34:58,475
Stay on your toes!

723
00:34:58,575 --> 00:34:59,575
Yes, Chef.

724
00:34:59,576 --> 00:35:01,974
Wash the radish and remove the peel.

725
00:35:01,975 --> 00:35:03,944
- Okay.
- After that... Come here.

726
00:35:03,945 --> 00:35:05,045
It's something important.

727
00:35:05,275 --> 00:35:06,415
This.

728
00:35:06,485 --> 00:35:08,344
(Making carvings on shiitake mushrooms)

729
00:35:08,345 --> 00:35:10,115
- Go like this.
- Okay.

730
00:35:11,585 --> 00:35:12,785
- Do you think you can do it?
- Yes.

731
00:35:13,525 --> 00:35:15,855
Okay. I will go make two.

732
00:35:17,025 --> 00:35:19,755
(Thank goodness. I almost got scolded.)

733
00:35:20,195 --> 00:35:22,095
(Yoon Si Yoon)

734
00:35:22,595 --> 00:35:24,895
Let's try not to get into trouble on the last day.

735
00:35:25,565 --> 00:35:27,235
(Laughing)

736
00:35:27,305 --> 00:35:29,934
I won't make any reasons to get scolded.

737
00:35:29,935 --> 00:35:30,935
(Laughing)

738
00:35:31,075 --> 00:35:33,605
Since it's the last day, Si Yoon should work the kitchen.

739
00:35:33,675 --> 00:35:34,944
(What?)

740
00:35:34,945 --> 00:35:36,375
I won't get scolded no matter what.

741
00:35:37,075 --> 00:35:38,475
Really? Try your best.

742
00:35:40,645 --> 00:35:42,414
I'll show everyone how perfect I am...

743
00:35:42,415 --> 00:35:43,855
and move Chef Paik.

744
00:35:44,285 --> 00:35:45,285
You'll see.

745
00:35:45,286 --> 00:35:47,225
(Laughing)

746
00:35:49,055 --> 00:35:52,195
(Is Chef Paik suddenly turning on the grill?)

747
00:35:52,925 --> 00:35:55,095
- Are you going to grill them all?
- Yes.

748
00:35:55,595 --> 00:35:58,195
(Is he grilling the meat to make braised beef ribs?)

749
00:35:58,765 --> 00:36:01,835
(Today's beef cut is sirloin.)

750
00:36:02,665 --> 00:36:07,045
(It's not as thin as regular Korean beef ribs.)

751
00:36:09,075 --> 00:36:12,375
(He will grill them first to make them softer.)

752
00:36:12,815 --> 00:36:17,315
(The fat he collected while preparing the meat)

753
00:36:17,915 --> 00:36:20,685
(Throwing pieces on the grill)

754
00:36:20,955 --> 00:36:23,354
- Grease it first.
- Okay.

755
00:36:23,355 --> 00:36:25,125
(Greasing the grill with the fat)

756
00:36:30,195 --> 00:36:32,795
(Grilled and braised beef ribs is born.)

757
00:36:33,535 --> 00:36:36,205
(Sugar is going on top of the meat!)

758
00:36:37,135 --> 00:36:40,705
(Once touched by sugar, it promotes Maillard reaction.)

759
00:36:41,245 --> 00:36:45,075
(Thanks to caramelization, it will become flavorful.)

760
00:36:49,245 --> 00:36:54,525
(The beef sirloin looks nice and brown.)

761
00:36:54,725 --> 00:36:55,855
Take this over there.

762
00:36:56,255 --> 00:36:57,395
Okay.

763
00:36:57,955 --> 00:37:01,195
(Adding enough water to completely cover the meat)

764
00:37:01,825 --> 00:37:04,295
(Going on the stovetop right away)

765
00:37:05,735 --> 00:37:09,505
(Boiling it on high heat)

766
00:37:09,865 --> 00:37:13,945
(Huge spoonfuls of ground garlic)

767
00:37:17,275 --> 00:37:20,645
(Radish and onion will give it a deep flavor.)

768
00:37:21,085 --> 00:37:23,455
(Add some starch syrup by squeezing the bottle.)

769
00:37:23,915 --> 00:37:26,315
(Dark soy sauce and soy sauce for color and salty taste)

770
00:37:26,725 --> 00:37:30,125
(Salt and honey will boost its sweet and salty charms.)

771
00:37:31,195 --> 00:37:34,965
(Carrots and shiitake mushrooms are a must for braised beef ribs.)

772
00:37:35,425 --> 00:37:38,565
(Also, king oyster mushroom with Chef Paik's portrait!)

773
00:37:39,265 --> 00:37:42,565
(Boil them all together.)

774
00:37:43,035 --> 00:37:45,675
(Braised beef ribs are ready.)

775
00:37:45,875 --> 00:37:47,605
Tteokbokki. We have to make tteokbokki.

776
00:37:48,345 --> 00:37:50,874
- John, cut some fish cakes for me.
- Yes?

777
00:37:50,875 --> 00:37:52,315
- Fish cakes?
- Yes.

778
00:37:53,645 --> 00:37:55,285
Long or triangles?

779
00:37:55,915 --> 00:37:57,515
I like the triangles.

780
00:37:57,815 --> 00:37:59,255
He didn't tell us which,

781
00:37:59,385 --> 00:38:01,354
- Okay.
- but we'll get scolded either way.

782
00:38:01,355 --> 00:38:02,884
Okay. I'll get scolded with the triangles.

783
00:38:02,885 --> 00:38:05,155
No, that won't happen.

784
00:38:05,225 --> 00:38:06,595
Don't worry. What's wrong with you?

785
00:38:06,965 --> 00:38:09,564
(The original members are laughing.)

786
00:38:09,565 --> 00:38:10,665
He's a rookie.

787
00:38:14,005 --> 00:38:15,865
Now, who will be the first to get yelled at?

788
00:38:16,735 --> 00:38:17,834
It's always Jang Woo.

789
00:38:17,835 --> 00:38:21,075
(It's Jang Woo, of course.)

